President Barack Obama and Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif of Pakistan held discussions in Washington, D.C., reaffirming the commitment to an enduring U.S.-Pakistan partnership and addressing evolving threats in South Asia. They expressed their desire to expand the bilateral relationship in areas such as trade, education, energy, climate change, and counterterrorism. The leaders emphasized the importance of democracy, economic growth, and regional integration. They also discussed the need for education, civil society cooperation, and global health initiatives. The leaders highlighted the significance of regional security, counterterrorism efforts, and promoting peace and stability in the region. They acknowledged the importance of improving Pakistan-India relations and addressing outstanding disputes. The leaders recognized the importance of cybersecurity, strategic stability, nuclear security, and nonproliferation. Overall, both leaders affirmed their commitment to working together to address issues of mutual interest and strengthen the U.S.-Pakistan partnership.